<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, December 28 (Xinhua) -- Four Iraqi soldiers were
killed and seven others injured in U.S. missile attacks on
Monday, said an Iraqi military spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said U.S. war planes flying from Turkey violated
Iraqi air space in the so-called no-fly zone in the north of Iraq
and launched missiles at Iraqi air defense positions.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi News Agency quoted the spokesman as saying that at
10:25 a.m. local time, enemy planes violated Iraqi airspace in
the north and flew close to Iraqi air defense positions.
</P>
<P>
He said that at 1:37 p.m., enemy planes violated Iraqi air
space again and flew to the same area and launched missiles at
Iraqi air defense positions. Iraqi soldiers fought back
courageously, said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
After the 1991 Gulf War touched off by Iraqi invasion of
Kuwait, the U.S. and Britain set up no-fly zones in the north and
south of Iraq with a claimed aim of protecting Kurdish minorities
in the north and Shiite Muslims in the south from Iraqi
government's attacks.
</P>
<P>
Iraqi Vice President Taha Yassin Ramadhan said on Sunday that
Iraq would not recognize the no-fly zones and would fire on enemy
planes violating Iraqi airspace.
</P>
<P>
He said the no-fly zones were set up by the U.S. and Britain
unilaterally and without the authorization of the U.N. Security
Council. 
