<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India, Sri Lanka Sign Free Trade Pact </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, December 28 (Xinhua) -- India and Sri Lanka Monday
evening signed a free trade pact for enhancing bilateral trade
relations.
</P>
<P>
Visiting Sri Lankan President Chandrika Kumaratunga and Indian
Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee signed the agreement after
they gave instructions to respective officials to overcome
last-minute differences on the issue.
</P>
<P>
The new pact, the first of its kind in South Asian countries,
provides for three-year phase-out of all tariffs by India and
removal of tariffs by Sri Lanka over an eight-year period. It will
come into effect from March 1 next year.
</P>
<P>
It envisages annual review and safeguards, including a negative
list, to ensure minimum 35 percent value-addition of imports to
prevent third country products flooding markets in either country.
The loss in revenue as a result of tariff reduction would be made
up by additional excise accruals through increased exports.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also signed a memorandum of understanding for
establishment of India-Sri Lanka foundation to promote interaction
in the fields of art, culture, trade and science and technology.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
