<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Low-Tar Cigarettes May Be Less Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
OTTAWA, December 28 (Xinhua) -- A new test revealed that
low-tar cigarettes may actually cause more heart and lung damages
than regular cigarettes, because smokers inhale and smoke more
after switching to low-tar brands.
</P>
<P>
The test, developed by Canada's British Columbia health
researchers, showed that smokers take deeper and more puffs after
they switch to the so-called mild cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
As a result, they are not doing themselves any health favors
by changing to low-tar brands.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Health officials said the new test showed tobacco
companies have tricked smokers into thinking a switch would
reduce the risks to their health.
</P>
<P>
They add this underscores the need for clearer warnings on
cigarette packaging, and urge tobacco companies to publicize the
latest research result on low-tar cigarettes as well as the
cigarette ingredients. 
</P>
</TEXT>
