in the mid-term polls in November 1994 is expected to be dissolved
for general elections by mid-April 1999.
</P>
<P>
The 11-member cabinet comprising the Nepali Congress, the
Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxism-Leninism, CPN-UML) and
the Nepal Sadbhavana Party was formed with the objective of
conducting free, fair and impartial elections.
</P>
<P>
The 10 ministers appointed last Friday were sworn in Monday.
</P>
<P>
Under the country's Constitution, a new government must obtain
the vote of confidence in the Lower House of Parliament within 30
days of its formation. 
</P>
