<HEADLINE> 22 Million Nigerian Children Immunized Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, December 28 (Xinhua) -- About 22 million Nigerians
children were immunized against polio this year in this most
populous country in Africa, according to Health Minister Debo
Adeyemi.
</P>
<P>
Under the National Program of Immunization (NPI) introduced by
the Nigerian government in 1997, the country held two rounds of
massive immunization for children on November 4-5 and December
9-10, respectively, the official New Nigerian newspaper Monday
quoted the minister as saying.
</P>
<P>
The NPI was initiated to replace the Expanded Program of
Immunization sponsored by the United Nations Children's Fund
(UNICEF), a global effort to wipe out polio, a disease that often
results in paralysis on children.
</P>
<P>
Official sources said the response level to immunization in
Nigeria has shot up to over 90 percent, compared with 15 to 30
percent before the NPI was introduced.
</P>
<P>
The government had expected that about 25 million children
would be immunized during this year's National Immunization Days.
</P>
